  "text": "Drugs. Phenytoin sodium (5,5-diphenylhydantoin sodium salt; Katwijk Chemie, Katwijk, The Netherlands) was dissolved in distilled water alkalinized with NaOH and administered either as a 50 mg/kg i.p. dose (distribution experiment) or infused in 5 min as a 40 mg/kg i.v. dose (pharmacokinetic experiment). Tariquidar (XR9576.14; Xenova Limited, Slough, Berkshire, UK) was dissolved in 5% dextrose solution and orally administered (12 mg/kg). The administration volume was 3 ml/kg. This dose was based on previous reports showing reversal of P-gp-mediated resistance in mice and rats [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Phenytoin Distribution. Phenytoin brain/plasma ratios were measured in control and chronic epileptic rats that received PHT only (50 mg/kg i.p.) and were killed 1 (control, n ϭ 6; chronic epilepsy, n ϭ 6) or 2.5 (control, n ϭ 5; chronic epilepsy, n ϭ 5) h after PHT administration, when PHT plasma levels are considered to be within the therapeutic range (10 -20 g/ml). We also included a group of chronic epileptic rats that were pretreated with tariquidar (TQD) (12 mg/kg p.o.) 24 and 4.5 h before they received PHT (50 mg/kg i.p., n ϭ 4) and that were killed 1 h after PHT was administered. The following brain regions were dissected (ipsilateral to the stimulated site): septal and temporal hippocampus, parahippocampal cortex (which included the entorhinal cortex and parts of the perirhinal and posterior piriform cortex), olfactory bulb, and cerebellum. The parahippocampal cortex was removed by incision at the ventrocaudal part underneath the rhinal fissure until approximately 5 mm posterior to bregma. All material was frozen on dry ice and stored at Ϫ80°C until use. Samples were weighed and homogenized in methanol/water (60:40, v/v) and processed for HPLC as described previously [CITATION_3] .",
